summary: The Hays Code was a set of moral guidelines applied to American films from 1930 to 1968, created under Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America (MPPDA) president Will H. Hays. It enforced strict censorship on content like crime, sex, and religion to align movies with conservative values of the time. Though initially voluntary, its enforcement became rigorous under Joseph Breen in the 1930s, shaping Hollywood's 'Golden Age' productions. The code was eventually abandoned in 1968, replaced by the modern MPAA film rating system due to shifting cultural norms.
